problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in computer science would. Completely simplify and rationalize the denominator: $$\frac{\sqrt{160}}{\sqrt{252}}\times\frac{\sqrt{245}}{\sqrt{108}}$$
gpt_response:
To simplify the expression, we first recognize that we can factor out any perfect squares from under the square roots:

$$\frac{\sqrt{160}}{\sqrt{252}}\times\frac{\sqrt{245}}{\sqrt{108}}\\
=\frac{\sqrt{16 \times 10}}{\sqrt{36 \times 7}}\times\frac{\sqrt{49 \times 5}}{\sqrt{36 \times 3}}\\
=\frac{\sqrt{16}\times\sqrt{10}}{\sqrt{36}\times\sqrt{7}}\times\frac{\sqrt{49}\times\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{36}\times\sqrt{3}}\\
=\frac{4\sqrt{10}}{6\sqrt{7}}\times\frac{7\sqrt{5}}{6\sqrt{3}}\\
=\frac{28\sqrt{50}}{36\sqrt{21}}\\
=\frac{14\sqrt{2}}{18\sqrt{21}}$$

Therefore, the simplified expression is $$\frac{14\sqrt{2}}{18\sqrt{21}}$$.
